---
import ChapterShell from "../../../components/ChapterShell.astro";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import DiagramFigure from "../../../components/diagrams/DiagramFigure.astro";
import AheBoundaryKeystone from "../../../components/diagrams/AheBoundaryKeystone.astro";
import EvidenceExportFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/EvidenceExportFlow.astro";
import ManifestEvaluateFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ManifestEvaluateFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="06" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      If system improvement happens inside the interactive Runtime and cannot be falsified, a lucky
      successful run hardens into “evolution.” AHE places self-iteration outside the Runtime:
      evidence export, candidate evaluation, rollable lineage. Key line:
      <strong
        >Event Log makes experience replayable; the AHE boundary makes change falsifiable.</strong
      >
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§06 · Scene"
    title="From “this task failed” to “the next system should differ”"
    lede="A single Self-check repairs the current task; systemic failure needs an outer experimental boundary."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose four of ten long tasks fail in similar places: the Agent understands the goal, ends too
      early after a tool failure, and Self-check marks an incomplete result as acceptable. One Run can
      only fix the current task; one Self-check can only point at gaps within limited Turns. The real
      question: do these failures imply the system prompt, tool contract, context policy, or Headless
      policy itself must change?
    </p>
    <p>
      If you dump the entire trace into another model and let it edit the repo, you immediately ask:
      which version is being changed? Which files are control plane vs evidence plane? Is “fixed” a
      narrative or backed by failing cases and predictions? Did the candidate only memorize seen
      cases? How do you return to the previous stable lineage?
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§06 · Keystone"
    title="Self-iteration is an outer loop, not Runtime recursion"
    lede="The system being improved must not simultaneously be fact recorder, change proposer, and final judge."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · Runtime plane produces exportable evidence; Evolution plane proposes a restricted manifest; independent evaluation keeps or rolls back."
      alt="Left Runtime plane (task→events→projection→read-only export), right dashed Evolution plane (AHE Controller, Change Manifest, independent evaluation); invariant: Event Log replays experience; AHE boundary makes change falsifiable."
    >
      <AheBoundaryKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Runtime plane</strong> — executes model/tool interaction; records events, permissions,
        artifacts, and task state; serves the current user Turn.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Evolution plane</strong> — aggregates evidence across runs, proposes candidate changes,
        compares baseline vs candidate; does not serve the current Turn.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="experience"
    label="§06 · Experience"
    title="Event Log becomes an experience base, not only a recovery base"
    lede="AHE should not swallow unbounded JSONL; normalize through TaskRun projection first."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · Read-only export chain: Events → Project → Normalize → Bind target → Export CLI."
      alt="Five-step evidence export pipeline ending in a read-only CLI."
    >
      <EvidenceExportFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Evidence export chain">Runtime / Task Events
        ↓ project
TaskRunProjection
        ↓ normalize and classify
Harness Results + Lineage + Trace Index + Failure Digest
        ↓ bind to
Target Snapshot</pre>
    <p>
      Projection provides stable task semantics (final status, artifacts, Self-check, workspace
      observation, score authority) without replacing original facts. An index layer helps the
      controller locate failure classes and lineage gaps; when explicitly requested, a raw-trace layer
      returns to canonical Runtime Events to verify the projection did not omit causal links — the
      third payoff of the first five chapters’ log-first architecture: history can be re-interpreted by
      a new projection.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Evolution aside</p>
      <p>
        AHE self-iteration architecture chapter land:
        <a href="/history/pr/776">maka:pr:776</a>
        (docs: add AHE self-iteration architecture chapter). Target protocol / evidence export
        implementations:
        <a href="/history/pr/411">maka:pr:411</a>,
        <a href="/history/pr/413">maka:pr:413</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="target"
    label="§06 · Target"
    title="Declare first what may be improved"
    lede="The most dangerous default is “the whole repository may be changed.”"
  >
    <p>
      <code>MakaAheTargetSnapshot</code> explicitly lists understandable components (system prompt,
      heavy-task policy, tool contracts, context management, permission policy, headless evaluation,
      …), each with <code>sourceRefs</code>. The sharpest read-only surface is
      <code>maka-runtime-evidence</code>:
      <strong
        >the ledger that produces judgment criteria must not simultaneously be a candidate patch
        target</strong
      >
      — otherwise the easiest “improvement” is to rewrite scoring, delete failures, or make evidence
      friendlier to the candidate.
    </p>
    <p>
      Snapshot identity binds managed source bytes and component topology (content identity), not the
      timestamp of an export action. Same source and topology → same <code>snapshotId</code>; any
      registered source change → id change.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="current"
    label="§06 · Current"
    title="What Current can do, and what Target still lacks"
    lede="Do not claim Maka already rewrites its own code unattended."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · Manifest → independent evaluate → Accept/Rollback; evolution forms lineage outside Runtime."
      alt="Five steps: Target snap, Manifest, Independent eval, Accept?, Lineage."
    >
      <ManifestEvaluateFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      Current: declare a source-backed target surface; export authority-bearing results, trace index,
      messages, and failure digest from TaskRun projection; validate restricted change manifests.
      Evidence export CLI is a read-only boundary — it reads existing stores and does not re-run
      tasks.
    </p>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current vs Target</p>
      <p>
        Target: an external AHE controller fully runs snapshot → analyze → candidate patch → evaluate
        → accept or rollback, forming recoverable lineage. Prompt Optimization Loop and similar in-repo
        patterns are adjacent implementations — not proof that a general unattended evolution system
        is complete.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <div slot="outline">
    <ul class="outline-list">
      <li>Present: keystone + evidence export + manifest/evaluate/rollback flows</li>
      <li>
        Aside: <a href="/history/pr/776">maka:pr:776</a>
      </li>
      <li>Still open: a11y pass — do not mark checklist complete</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</ChapterShell>

